{
  "doc_id": "57720",
  "text": "Japan has incurred greater than 90% declines in grasslands in the past 100 years [CITATION_1] . Grasslands covered greater than 10% of the nation's land surface until 100 years ago and were maintained by people to produce forage for livestock, natural fertilizer and thatching for rooves [CITATION_2] . The majority of Japan's modern and medieval grasslands were therefore seminatural grasslands (called 'grasslands' unless otherwise stated). However, agricultural and social modernization resulted in grasslands being converted to plantations or being replaced by natural forests (due to the warm and wet climate, abandonment leads to grasslands succeeding into forests [CITATION_3] ). Now, 67% of Japan's land is forested [CITATION_4] , and grasslands have become one of the nation's most endangered ecosystems (although they have been maintained by humans), supporting many species of conservation concern [CITATION_5] .",
